 Catch up on Chapter 1 here.  2017: The Black Empowerment Foundation On 7 April 2017, 25,000 people arrived by bus, by train and on foot at the Union Buildings in Pretoria to deliver a resolute message: Zuma Must Fall. Barely noticed, a much smaller group gathered outside the Pietermaritzburg City Hall. Instead of slogans or demands, most of these protestors carried posters advertising the march they were already attending, which invited people â€œto gather in solidarity to support the efforts of the honourable president Jacob G Zuma, to effect radical economic transformation and economic emancipation by 2021â€. In the front of the group a man in a black suit was holding a megaphone, while behind him the group of roughly 30 protestors chanted: â€œBEF! BEF! BEF!â€ The Black Empowerment Foundation (BEF) was registered as a non-profit organisation just three months earlier, in January 2017, and described itself as a â€œlobby groupâ€ fighting for â€œthe economic emancipation of black South Africans in the greater economyâ€. So new was the group, Ibrahim Shaik â€“ the man holding the megaphone â€“ wrongly told police it was the â€œBlack Economic Foundationâ€.  Shaik was not on our radar until recently, but messages from a WhatsApp group reveal he has powerful friends. â€œI love this young lion in case others dont know him,â€ Dudu Myeni, the former chair of South Africa Airways, posted on the â€œTwitter Stormâ€ WhatsApp group, adding: â€œIbrahimâ€¦.for Youth League NEC.â€ (More on this WhatsApp group later.) Shaik works for Amalgamated Tobacco Manufacturing, a cigarette manufacturer in Pietermaritzburg that, until late 2018, counted Edward Zuma, the former presidentâ€™s son, as one of its directors. â€œI am a rights activist, a human rights activist, was involved for the last eight years with Edward Zuma,â€ Shaik told us last month. â€œI also have a non-profit organisation called A Better World Allianceâ€¦ Iâ€™m a politician, human rights activist. I wear quite a few caps